'''Cheap meat''' is a term used to describe relatively inexpensive [[meat]] (e.g. fatty cuts of lamb or [[mutton]])<ref>Deborah Gewertz, Frederick Errington, ''Cheap Meat: Flap Food Nations in the Pacific Islands'', University of California Press, 2010. {{ISBN|0520260937}}</ref> or to indicate that the consumer price of meat does not include the overall costs of industrial meat production. The term cheap meat is then either related to subsidies,<ref>[http://www.dw.de/the-high-cost-of-cheap-meat/a-16513500 Deutsche Welle, Agriculture – The high cost of cheap meat, January, 11 2013]</ref> to [[Externality#External costs|hidden costs]]<ref>[[Meat Atlas|Meat Atlas 2014 – Facts and figures about the animals we eat]], chapter: ''The hidden cost of steak'', page 20, download [https://www.foeeurope.org/sites/default/files/publications/foee_hbf_meatatlas_jan2014.pdf Meat Atlas] as pdf</ref> or to non-material costs ("moral cost") of meat production. Non-material costs can be related to issues such as animal welfare (e.g. treatment of animals, over-breeding).<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/sep/04/why-cheap-meat-costs-earth The Guardian, Why cheap meat costs the Earth, 4 September 2013]</ref><ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/10/animal-cruelty-is-the-price_n_4418270.html Huffington Post / RollingStone, ''Animal Cruelty Is The Price We Pay For Cheap Meat'', 12/10/2013]</ref><ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/environment/articles/2013/06/21/3786161.htm ABC Australia, ''How much is cheap meat really costing us?'', 21 Jun 2013]</ref> The term is used by critics of the meat industry.<ref>[http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-09-24/health/ct-met-cheap-protein--20100923_1_factory-farms-cafos-salmonella-outbreak Chicago tribune, The costs of cheap meat – Critics of factory farms say we pay a high price for low-cost food, September 24, 2010]</ref>
The meat industry is subsidized with billions of dollars by governments who support their meat industries. The [[OECD]] estimates the total "producer support" in OECD countries for 2012 as follows: 18bn USD for beef and veal, 7.3bn USD for pigmeat, 6.5bn USD for poultry and 1bn USD for sheepmeat (provisional numbers).<ref>[http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/agriculture-and-food/agricultural-policy-monitoring-and-evaluation-2013_agr_pol-2013-en OECD, Agricultural Policy Monitoring and Evaluation 2013, 2013, p. 317, table: "OECD: Producer Single Commodity Transfers (USD)"]</ref> Hidden costs of meat production can be related to the [[environmental impact of meat production]] and to the effect on human health (such as [[Antibiotic use in livestock|resistant antibiotics]]).<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/03/opinion/03fri3.html?_r=0 The New York Times, The High Cost of Cheap Meat, June 2 2011]</ref>
==Bibliography== * Lymbery, Philip. ''[[farmageddon_(book)|Farmageddon: The True Cost of Cheap Meat]]'', Bloomsbury Publishing, 2014. {{ISBN|1408846446}}<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jan/29/farmageddon-cost-cheap-meat-lymbery-review The Guardian, ''Farmageddon: The True Cost of Cheap Meat by Philip Lymbery – review'', 31 January 2014]</ref>
